{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532965"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:31:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:31:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14729"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14729"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.05,0.04,0.03,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113134"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7422"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95161"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18126"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46428"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113134"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review six weeks after an ST-elevation myocardial infarction. He has a history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His medications include aspirin 100 mg daily, ticagrelor 90 mg twice daily, metoprolol 50 mg twice daily, ramipril 10 mg daily, metformin 1000 mg twice daily, empagliflozin 10 mg daily, and atorvastatin 80 mg daily. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His recent lipid profile shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etotal cholesterol 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELDL-cholesterol 1.7 mmol/L (0.0-3.4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDL-cholesterol 1.1 mmol/L (\u0026gt;1.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etriglycerides 1.5 mmol/L (0.0-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current management","Add fenofibrate","Switch to rosuvastatin","Add a PCSK9 inhibitor","Add ezetimibe"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has had a recent myocardial infarction and is already on maximum-dose atorvastatin (80 mg daily). Despite this high-intensity statin therapy, his LDL-cholesterol remains at 1.7 mmol/L. For patients with established atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease (ASCVD), current guidelines recommend achieving both an LDL-cholesterol \u0026lt;1.4 mmol/L AND at least 50% reduction from baseline, whichever target is lower. This patient has not achieved the absolute target of \u0026lt;1.4 mmol/L, necessitating additional lipid-lowering therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd ezetimibe\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Ezetimibe inhibits cholesterol absorption in the small intestine and provides an additional 15-20% reduction in LDL-cholesterol when added to statin therapy. It is well-tolerated and has been shown to reduce cardiovascular events when added to statins in patients with recent acute coronary syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current management\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the patient has not achieved the recommended LDL-cholesterol target despite maximum statin therapy. Leaving the LDL-cholesterol at 1.7 mmol/L would expose the patient to unnecessary cardiovascular risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd fenofibrate\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for hypertriglyceridaemia. The patient\u0027s triglyceride is within the target for patients with established ASCVD (less than 1.7 mmol/L). Fenofibrate has a limited effect on LDL-cholesterol and has not been shown to reduce cardiovascular events when added to statins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitch to rosuvastatin\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide a significant additional benefit as the patient is already on maximum-dose atorvastatin. Both atorvastatin 80 mg and rosuvastatin 40 mg are considered high-intensity statin therapy with similar LDL-lowering efficacy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd a PCSK9 inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g. evolocumab) may be considered if the LDL-cholesterol target is not achieved despite maximum statin therapy plus ezetimibe. These injectable medications are highly effective but are reserved for patients who have not achieved targets with oral therapy due to their cost and route of administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stepwise approach to lipid management in secondary prevention typically follows: (1) high-intensity statin therapy, (2) addition of ezetimibe if targets not met, (3) consideration of PCSK9 inhibitors if targets still not achieved. This approach aims to balance efficacy, tolerability, and cost-effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The target LDL-cholesterol level in patients with established ASCVD is \u003C1.4 mmol/L AND at least 50% reduction from baseline.","If LDL-cholesterol targets are not achieved with maximum-dose statin therapy, ezetimibe should be added as the next step."],"references":["Brieger D, Cullen L, Briffa T, et al.; other members of the Heart Foundation Working Group. Electronic address: clinicalevidence@heartfoundation.org.au. National Heart Foundation of Australia \u0026 Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Comprehensive Australian Clinical Guideline for Diagnosing and Managing Acute Coronary Syndromes 2025. Heart Lung Circ. 2025 Apr;34(4):309-397. Available at: https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/for-professionals/acs-guideline?tab=4#Lipid-modifying%20therapy","Practical guide to pharmacological lipid management | Heart Foundation [Internet]. [cited 2025 Sept 7]. Available from: https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/heart-health-check-toolkit/pharmacological-lipid"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95161"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14729"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95161"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-09T19:48:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-09T19:48:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7422"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113134"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{